==Functions==

52. Let <math>f(x)=x^2</math>.
{{question-answer|question=a. Compute <math>f(0)</math> and <math>f(2)</math>.|answer=<math>f(0)=0</math>, <math>f(2)=4</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=b. What are the domain and range of <math>f</math>?|answer=The domain is <math>(-\infty,\infty)</math>; the range is <math>[0,\infty)</math>,}}
{{question-answer|question=c. Does <math>f</math> have an inverse? If so, find a formula for it.|answer=No, since <math>f</math> isn't one-to-one; for example, <math>f(-1)=f(1)=1</math>.}}

53. Let <math>f(x)=x+2</math>, <math>g(x)=1/x</math>.<br/>
:a. Give formulae for
{{question-answer|question=i. <math>f+g</math>|answer=<math>(f+g)(x)=x+2+1/x=(x^2+2x+1)/x</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=ii. <math>f-g</math>|answer=<math>(f-g)(x)=x+2-1/x=(x^2+2x-1)/x</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=iii. <math>g-f</math>|answer=<math>(g-f)(x)=1/x-x-2=(1-x^2-2x)/x</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=iv. <math>f\times g</math>|answer=<math>(f\times g)(x)=(x+2)/x</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=v. <math>f/g</math>|answer=<math>(f/g)(x)=x(x+2)</math> provided <math>x\ne0</math>. Note that 0 is not in the domain of <math>f/g</math>, since it's not in the domain of <math>g</math>, and you can't divide by something that doesn't exist!}}
{{question-answer|question=vi. <math>g/f</math>|answer=<math>(g/f)(x)=1/[x(x+2)]</math>. Although 0 is still not in the domain, we don't need to state it now, since 0 isn't in the domain of the expression <math>1/[x(x+2)]</math> either.}}
{{question-answer|question=vii. <math>f\circ g</math>|answer=<math>(f\circ g)(x)=1/x+2=(2x+1)/x</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=viii. <math>g\circ f</math>|answer=<math>(g\circ f)(x)=1/(x+2)</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=b. Compute <math>f(g(2))</math> and <math>g(f(2))</math>.|answer=<math>f(g(2))=5/2</math>; <math>g(f(2))=1/4</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=c. Do <math>f</math> and <math>g</math> have inverses? If so, find formulae for them.|answer=Yes; <math>f^{-1}(x)=x-2</math> and <math>g^{-1}(x)=1/x</math>. Note that <math>g</math> and its inverse are the same.}}

{{question-answer|question=54. Does this graph represent a function? [[Image:Sinx over x.svg]]|answer=As pictured, by the Vertical Line test, this graph represents a function.}}

