{{Calculus/Top Nav|Integration techniques/Numerical Approximations|Area}}
{{Calculus/TOC}}

==Integration of Polynomials==
Evaluate the following:
{{question-answer|question=1. <math>\int (x^2-2)^{2}\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\begin{align}\int(x^{2}-2)^{2}dx&=\int(x^{4}-4x^{2}+4)dx\\
&=\mathbf{\frac{x^{5}}{5}-\frac{4x^{3}}{3}+4x+C}\end{align}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=2. <math>\int 8x^3\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\begin{align}\int8x^{3}dx&=\frac{8x^{4}}{4}+C\\
&=\mathbf{2x^{4}+C}\end{align}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=3. <math>\int (4x^2+11x^3)\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\int(4x^{2}+11x^{3})dx=\mathbf{\frac{4x^{3}}{3}+\frac{11x^{4}}{4}+C} </math>}}

{{question-answer|question=4. <math>\int (31x^{32}+4x^3-9x^4) \,dx</math>|answer=<math>\begin{align}\int(31x^{32}+4x^{3}-9x^{4})dx&=\frac{31x^{33}}{33}+\frac{4x^{4}}{4}-\frac{9x^{5}}{5}+C\\
&=\mathbf{\frac{31x^{33}}{33}+x^{4}-\frac{9x^{5}}{5}+C}\end{align}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=5. <math>\int 5x^{-2}\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\begin{align}\int5x^{-2}dx&=\frac{5x^{-1}}{-1}+C\\
&=\mathbf{-\frac{5}{x}+C}\end{align}</math>}}

==Indefinite Integration==
Find the general antiderivative of the following:
{{question-answer|question=6. <math>\int (\cos x+\sin x)\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\int (\cos x+\sin x)\, dx=\mathbf{\sin x-\cos x+C}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=7. <math>\int 3\sin x\, dx </math>|answer=<math>\int 3\sin x\, dx=\mathbf{-3\cos(x)+C}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=8. <math>\int (1+\tan^2 x)\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\begin{align}\int(1+\tan^{2}x)dx&=\int\sec^{2}x dx\\
&=\mathbf{\tan x+C}\end{align}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=9. <math>\int (3x-\sec^2 x)\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\int (3x-\sec^2 x)\, dx=\mathbf{\frac{3x^{2}}{2}-\tan x+C}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=10. <math>\int -e^x\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\int -e^x\, dx=\mathbf{-e^{x}+C}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=11. <math>\int 8e^x\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\int 8e^x\, dx=\mathbf{8e^{x}+C}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=12. <math>\int \frac1{7x}\, dx</math>|answer=<math>\int \frac1{7x}\, dx=\mathbf{\frac{1}{7}\ln|x|+C}</math>}}

{{question-answer|question=13. <math>\int \frac1{x^2+a^2}\, dx</math>|answer=Let
:<math>x=a\tan\theta;\qquad dx=a\sec^{2}\theta d\theta</math>
Then
:<math>\begin{align}\int\frac{1}{x^{2}+a^{2}}dx&=\int\frac{a\sec^{2}\theta d\theta}{a^{2}(\tan^{2}\theta+1)}\\
&=\int\frac{\sec^{2}\theta d\theta}{a\sec^{2}\theta}\\
&=\frac{1}{a}\int d\theta\\
&=\frac{\theta}{a}+C\\
&=\mathbf{\frac{1}{a}\arctan\frac{x}{a}+C}\end{align}</math>}}

==Integration by parts==
{{question-answer|question=14. Consider the integral <math>\int \sin(x) \cos(x)\,dx</math>. Find the integral in two different ways. (a) Integrate by parts with <math>u=\sin(x)</math> and <math> v' =\cos(x)</math>. (b) Integrate by parts with <math>u=\cos(x)</math> and <math> v' =\sin(x)</math>. Compare your answers. Are they the same?|answer=(a)
:<math>u=\sin x;\qquad du=\cos x dx</math>
:<math>v=\sin x;\qquad dv=\cos x dx</math>
:<math>\begin{array}{ccc}
\int\sin x\cos x dx=\sin^{2}x-\int\sin x\cos x dx & \implies & 2\int\sin x\cos x dx=\sin^{2}x\\
 & \implies & \int\sin x\cos x dx=\mathbf{\frac{\sin^{2}x}{2}}
\end{array}</math><br/>
(b)
:<math>u=\cos x;\qquad du=-\sin x dx</math>
:<math>v=-\cos x\qquad dv=\sin x dx</math>
:<math>\begin{array}{ccc}
\int\sin x\cos x dx=-\cos^{2}x-\int\sin x\cos x dx & \implies & 2\int\sin x\cos x dx=-\cos^{2}x\\
 & \implies & \int\sin x\cos x dx=\mathbf{-\frac{\cos^{2}x}{2}}
\end{array}</math>
Notice that the answers in parts (a) and (b) are not equal. However, since indefinite integrals include a constant term, we expect that the answers we found will differ by a constant. Indeed
:<math>\frac{\sin^{2}x}{2}-(-\frac{\cos^{2}x}{2})=\frac{\sin^{2}x+\cos^{2}x}{2}=\frac{1}{2}</math>}}

